What is Jenkins?
Jenkins is an open-source automation tool mainly used for:
  -Contineous Integration (CI)
  -Contineous Delivery (CD)
  -Build Automation
  -Deployment Automation
  -Testing Automation

Note: Jenkins helps automate software development lifecycle

"Jenkins is a tool that automatically builds, tests, and deploy application whenever developers make code changes"

Why Jenkins is Important?
---------------------------
Before Jenkins:
-Developer writes code
-Manually build application
-Manually test
-Manually deploy
-Takes more time
-Human errors happen

After Jenkins:
1.Developer push code to githu
2.Jenkins automatically:
  pulls code
  builds application
  Runs tests
  Deploy to server

Note: Everything becomes automated


Real-Time Example:
-------------------
Scenario: E-Commerce Website
Company uses:
-GitHub ---> Source code
-Jenkins ---> Automation CI/CD
-AWS EC2 ---> Application server
-AWS S3 ----> Store build artifacts
-Docker ---> Containerization

WorkFlow:
----------
Developer push code to GitHub.

Jenkins automatically:
1.Detects code change
2.Downloads latest code
3.Build application
4.Runs tests
5.Create Docker images
6.Pushes image to AWS ECR
7.Deploys application to ECS

This is called : CI/CD Pipelines

Jenkins Architecture: Main Components
--------------------------------------
1.Jenkins Master (Controller)
-Managing Jobs
-Sechudling builds
-Managing plugins
-Monitorning Agents

2.Jenkins Agent(worker node)
-Executing build jobs
-Running tests
-Deplpoyments

Jenkins Pipeline Flow:
----------------------
Developer->GitHub->Jenkins Trigger->Build Application->Run Tests->Create Artifacts->Deploy to AWS->Application Live

Features of Jenkins:
---------------------
-Open source free to use
-Plugin support thousands of plugins support
-CI/CD automation
-Easy Integration
-Pipeline as code : jenkinsfile

